1.1 Bin size

bin size

\(\begin{aligned} k= \left[ \frac{max x - min x}{h} \right]\\ \end{aligned}\)

square root

\(\begin{aligned} k = \left[ \sqrt{n} \right]\\ \end{aligned}\)

sturges formula

\(\begin{aligned} k = \left[ log_2 n \right] + 1\\ \end{aligned}\)

Rice rule

Doannes formula

\(k = 1 + log_{2}(n) + log_{2}(1+\frac{|g_{1}|}{\sigma_{g_1}})\)

scotts rule

\(h = \frac{3.5\hat{\sigma}}{n^{1/3}}\)

freedman-diaconiss rule \(2(IQR){n}^{10}\) epa

library(varrank)
bin.doane<-discretization(mtcars$mpg, discretization.method = "doane", frequency = FALSE)

2 graphics package

hist(x, breaks = "Sturges", freq = NULL, probability = !freq, include.lowest = TRUE,
     right = TRUE, density = NULL, angle = 45, col = NULL, border = NULL,
     main = paste("Histogram of" , xname), xlim = range(breaks), ylim = NULL,
     xlab = xname, ylab, axes = TRUE, plot = TRUE, labels = FALSE, nclass = NULL,
     warn.unused = TRUE, ...)

breaks argumet is one of:

. a vector giving the breakpoints between histogram cells,

. a function to compute the vector of breakpoints,

. a single number giving the number of cells for the histogram,

. a character string naming an algorithm to compute the number of cells (see Details),

. a function to compute the number of cells.

The default for breaks is Sturges. Other names for which algorithms are supplied are Scott and FD / Freedman-Diaconis

par(mfrow=c(1,4))
hist(pseudo, breaks = 10, main = "Pseudo Histogram - break=10", col = "steelblue")
hist(pseudo, breaks = 30, main = "Pseudo Histogram - break=30",col = "steelblue")

density plots

Density plots can be thought of as plots of smoothed histograms.

The smoothness is controlled by a bandwidth parameter that is analogous to the histogram binwidth.

Most density plots use a kernel density estimate, but there are other possible strategies; qualitatively the particular strategy rarely matters.

Compute the density data

pseudo.density <- density(pseudo)
pseudo.density
## 
## Call:
##  density.default(x = pseudo)
## 
## Data: pseudo (1000 obs.);    Bandwidth 'bw' = 0.4018
## 
##        x                y            
##  Min.   :-4.136   Min.   :1.506e-05  
##  1st Qu.:-1.374   1st Qu.:7.982e-03  
##  Median : 1.388   Median :9.127e-02  
##  Mean   : 1.388   Mean   :9.043e-02  
##  3rd Qu.: 4.149   3rd Qu.:1.462e-01  
##  Max.   : 6.911   Max.   :2.525e-01

plot density

plot(pseudo.density, frame = FALSE, col = "steelblue", main = "Pseudo Densiy Plot")

Fill the density plot using polygon()

plot(pseudo.density, frame = FALSE, col = "steelblue", main = "Pseudo Density Plot bw = 0.4") 
polygon(pseudo.density, col = "steelblue")

plot(density(pseudo, bw = 0.1), frame = FALSE,col = "steelblue", main = "Pseudo Density Plot bw = 0.1")

adding jittered rug

plot(density(pseudo, bw = 0.1), frame = FALSE, col = "steelblue", main = "Pseudo Density Plot bw = 0.1") 
rug(jitter(pseudo))

3 lattice package

histogram(x, data, allow.multiple, outer = TRUE, auto.key = FALSE,
          aspect = "fill", panel = lattice.getOption("panel.histogram"),
          prepanel, scales, strip, groups, xlab, xlim, ylab, ylim,
          type = c("percent", "count", "density"),
          nint = if (is.factor(x)) nlevels(x)
          else round(log2(length(x)) + 1),
          endpoints = extend.limits(range(as.numeric(x),
          finite = TRUE), prop = 0.04), breaks, equal.widths = TRUE,
          drop.unused.levels = lattice.getOption("drop.unused.levels"),
          ...,
          lattice.options = NULL, default.scales = list(),
          default.prepanel = lattice.getOption("prepanel.default.histogram"),
          subscripts, subset)

WVPlots packcage

library(WVPlots)
#DoubleHistogramPlot()
set.seed(34903490)
x = rnorm(50)
y = 0.5*x^2 + 2*x + rnorm(length(x))
frm = data.frame(x=x,y=y,yC=y>=as.numeric(quantile(y,probs=0.8)))
frm$absY <- abs(frm$y)
frm$posY = frm$y > 0
frm$costX = 1
WVPlots::DoubleHistogramPlot(mtcars, "mpeg", "cyl", title="Example double histogram plot")
d<-data.frame(x=mtcars$mpg)
threshold = 25
WVPlots::ShadedDensity(d, "x", threshold, tail="right", 
                       title="Example shaded density plot, right tail")
